author: @Aleem533
comment: Lahore, once celebrated as a culturally rich and historic city. It could have been a true powerhouse of tourism. heritage and centre of art lovers. Unfortunately, instead of modern infrastructure abd smart city planning, what we mostly see today is endless focus on heavy non-vegetarian, oily street food and superficial content creation. Compare this with India, where cities like Chandigarh, Gurugram, Noida, Dehradun, and Naya Raipur etc (more than 100 cities) have transformed remarkably in the post-independence era. Pakistan has not done justice to Lahoreâ€™s immense potentialâ€”it deserves far more than just narrow streets and food vlogs there! Thanks to the Blogger for showing real picture

author: @seekfortruth4979
comment:
I tried jaida Lassi once after all these vlogs let me tell you my experience too,
The top layer on the yogurt is always exposed and this shop is on the side of the street. All the dust, dog and donkey poo, flies,and you guys just saw a tractor pull a trash trolley right in front of this shop. Everything flies up and falls on top of this top layer of yogurt(malai). Second the guy who mixes it with the wooden spoon is mixing it along with all the previous dirt he already mixed in there. I had severe food poisoning for a week had to he hospitalized after this. So if you are not a local here I won't recommend you to drink this since the locals have built an immunity against all this dirt and poo

author: @VedantYadav-p5x
comment:
The fact that there are only two operational temples in all of Lahore makes me more rigid in my faith. As a Hindu, it pains me to know that the once wealthiest community in Lahore is now reduced to relying on just two temples. It fuels my anger and resentment when I see that India has the highest number of mosques in the world and that the Waqf Board is the third-largest landowner in the country. Meanwhile, my fellow Hindus are left with just two temples.
This is not about the mindset of two different countries towards their respective minorities; rather, it is about how a majority treats its own minorities. ğŸ˜I feel both fear and angerâ€”anger at the fact that despite everything being so evident, people sit silently as if they know nothing, and fear because my own people have abandoned the reality of their past and are busy with their lives. They coexist without resentment with those who have repeatedly attacked our faith, raped our women's, and  waged war against us with betrayal and deceit. Sikhs have forgotten the sacrifices of the Sikh Gurus, hindus forgotten plight of Kashmiri Pandits, and the countless injustices our religion has sufferedâ€”be it the Jizya tax or the horrifying reality of our women being sold in markets throughout history."And those who say, 'Itâ€™s history, forget it,' I feel like ripping their tongues out. Their voice doesnâ€™t even tremble while saying thisâ€”they donâ€™t stop to think about how their own ancestors once fought to protect our faith."How must they have lived in an era where only Hindus were forced to pay taxes? Purani Anarkali, androon shehr,  Choona  Mandi, Krishan nagar witnessed the lives of many such Umm-e-Laylas and Umm-e-Farwas.

You can enjoy the same dishes at restaurants that at least look visibly clean. 

Avoid eating from random stalls. Even if a roadside stall looks clean, the pollution in the air can contaminate the food and cause food poisoning or other infections, especially if tap water is used. This is simple common sense. Please avoid unnecessary adventures and stay safe. You are here to make good memories, not to end up in the hospital.

author: @chozusmakavelli
comment:
I'll tell you what made you sick:-
with any spice meal you need to balance it with any combination of cucumber, onions, yoghurt or lassi, to balance the heat from spice/meat/oil in your stomach. You need to balance the Geoff you eat.
Spice + spice + spice = explosions.
Raw onions in particular are a necessity with spicy food, they help with digestion. You're supposed to have a strand or two with every bite.
When we eat curry/biryani we alternate one bite with onion, one bite with cucumber.
Nearly every restaurant is on cloud coocoo land, they're supposed to give you salad with everything, but they don't unless you ask them, mofo's are "dain bread" (brain dead in ghetto), and goo oblivious to even advise you.
Most restaurants/eateries overload the spices/oil in everything so avoid eating too much spice and too much meat. 
if you get around to having a home cooked meal somewhere you will see the difference - you won't get sick from a home cooked meal.
Also don't overeat, avoid anything with mince meat, keep hydrated, eat plenty of fruit.

It consists of slow-cooked meat, mainly a shank cut of beef, lamb and mutton, or goat meat, as well as chicken and bone marrow. It is flavoured with long pepper (pippali), a relative of black pepper. author: @Photolover-t8h
comment: Regardless if tourists were rampant in Pakistan or not. Not taking money is a cultural thing in Pakistani culture.  Whether in Pakistan or outside of Pakistan. I am first generation Brit and even I have inherited that value. It is considered disrespectful to charge a guest or a friend any money because the implication is that if I did charge money then that person is not really someone who I seriously consider a guest or a friend. It is normal. So, if any Pakistani doesn't want to charge you any money no matter what country you're in, just accept their request and chill. It is normal for Pakistanis.

author: @makanmata
comment:
I'm assuming that you were accompanied by a man, but you should be careful not to leave anybody with the false impression that it is safe for a woman to walk the streets of Lahore alone. Most people in Lahore are completely welcoming and friendly, but it only takes one to ruin your life. There is a reason why you don't see women walking in the streets without male escorts. This is especially true at a place like Jeela, which gets - how to put this delicately? - the most ignorant element of society made up of the most credulous and uneducated people who are impressed with his cheap tricks.

As far as where else you should go, Nadeem Butt, Ilyas Dumba at Truck Adda,  Khan Baba, Jeda Lassi, Nashta at Haji Sahib Nihari Walay

author: @omerosdaskalos7708
comment:
ğŸ˜® oh ! Youre back there again ? Or have you left again already? Hard to keep track ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤£ 
If youre still in Lahore , you could possibly visit Kasur town nearby, to see the Sufi shrine of the poet Bullay Shah. And you should visit Shalimar Gardens (Mughal times) as well as the Lahore Fort/Badshahi Mosque. If youre willing to go a bit farther away you could also see ancient Harappa (ruins and small museum BC) . If you go to Islamabad, you can visit the Taxila museum and the Khanpur dam/lake and also Murree hill resort. Along the Lahore-Islamabad motorway you can visit Kallar Kahar , and Katas Raj (ancient Hindu temple with legendary tale) - and a half dozen orher places in that region. Youve already been up North to Chitral and the NW i think ? I think you can just focus on the Lahore-Islamabad area for now. Good luck. 
(BTW, youre navigating Lahore traffic well this time âœŒï¸)
(PPS - i note you've already been to the Badshahi Mosque in this vlog, so that's out anyhow)

author: @Sam12345-o
comment:
Hey Katie, 

I feel sorry upon how men were treating you inappropriately in this video. In all honesty, I am totally enraged. It's highly inappropriate to touch someone without their consent, let alone if it's a woman. In a Pakistani culture and also Islamically speaking, it's considered to be highly inappropriate when a man does that. If you are not related to a man,  e.g. if you're not their mother, daughter ,wife or sister; they are not even supposed to come into your radius or they are supposed to interact with you at a safe distance.

 You need to be more proactive about this and start yelling at them, on top of your lungs, and ask them to " pee-chey Hut-toh ( step back)". And stare back at them ( with your eyes popped out) . Please be very careful. 

Also the people you met in the video ,they are mostly lay men workers or underprivileged. They are illetrate ,uneducated and basically frustrated in their lives ( usually financial reasons ).

It's just like you're in America and in the middle of hillbillies , who are primarily homeless. So you can only imagine how unsafe that can be to be around them. So do not to go alone in the historic places. It's always a good idea to be escorted by someone or go in a group. 

Yes Alhumdulilah, We Pakistanis are super hospitable but that doesn't mean everyone will treat you the same. Having said that, I thoroughly enjoyed your video and keep up the good work ğŸ‘ğŸ»

author: @tibzig1
comment: My brother attended Aitchison College back in the mid 1970s. Lahore was still a wonderful place. Out family lived in Karachi but since he was a boarder in school, we would visit him three or four times a year. I still remember riding around on my chacha's Honda 175 motorcycle on Canal Road. Does anyone remember Vespas and the Honda 175s? Classic 2 wheelers.  My family moved to the US in 1982. The first time I visited Pakistan after moving there was in 2008 and it was quite a shock. The old Pakistan I knew no longer existed.  The overpopulation, traffic and the mentality of the people was radically different from what I remember from the 1970s and 1980s.  I have visited many times after 2008 but each time the old days just seem a misty dream. I am 61 now.

author: @mhaiderkhan2000
comment:
A sincere nostalgic memory of the childhood of my 60s. You explained these pics in plain language, but it went into deep through that refreshed my memory transparently. I can't express how much it agitated me. Definitely the city moved on to a different dimension, we call it development or improvement, but I am not sure how much it is true. People in this new era will not have the sense how cool it was as shown in these footages. Good that you saved those all as evidence. We breathed oxygen in the past now we breathe CO2 and dust. The people have now become mechanized like robots. There are a lot to say but what is the use: Thanks a lot Bilal for sharing these gems. I watch all of yours. Keep it going. 
Regards

comment:
A legend based on oral traditions holds thatÂ Lahore, known in ancient times asÂ NokharÂ (City of Lava inÂ Sanskrit),[1]Â was founded by PrinceÂ Lava,[2]Â the son of GoddessÂ SitaÂ and LordÂ Rama;Â KasurÂ was founded by his twin brother PrinceÂ Kusha.[3]Â To this day,Â Lahore FortÂ has a vacantÂ Lava templeÂ dedicated toÂ LavaÂ (also pronounced Loh, henceÂ Loh-awarÂ or "The Fort of Loh").[4LordÂ RamaÂ fightingÂ LavaÂ andÂ Kusha.

The oldest authentic document about Lahore was written anonymously in 982. It is calledÂ Hudud-i-AlamÂ (The Regions of the World).[5]Â In 1927 it was translated intoÂ EnglishÂ byÂ Vladimir Fedorovich MinorskyÂ and published in Lahore. In this document, Lahore is referred to as a smallÂ shehrÂ (city) with "impressive temples, large markets and huge orchards." It refers to "two major markets around which dwellings exist," and it also mentions "the mud walls that enclose these two dwellings to make it one." The original document is currently held in theÂ British Museum.[6]Â Lahore was called by different names throughout history. To date there is no conclusive evidence as to when it was founded. Some historians trace the history of the city as far back as 4000 years ago.[7]Â However, historically, it has been proved that Lahore is at least 2,000 years old. Lying on the main trade and invasion routes to South Asia, Lahore has been ruled and plundered by a number of dynasties and hordes.Â Ganga RamÂ is regarded as "the father of modern Lahore". siyapati ramchandra ki jai ğŸ™

I miss Lahore, I miss the hospitality of Lahore, I miss everything about Lahore.

author: @mansoorahmad1489
comment:
Lahore is a mystique. It has a night life that is not like any other city in the world. This night life does not have disco bars or night clubs. It has people sitting on streets and singing folk songs while using kitchen vessels as instruments. Great poets and artists like Nasir Kazmi and Munir Niazi and Saghar Siddiqui roaming on the streets. Spiritual healers moving nonchalantly among ordinary men. 

Well. At least it was like that forty years ago. Today's Lahore is mostly underpasses, overhead bridges and metros and too much traffic . But its charms is still there.

author: @sameerazenib9678
comment: Those kebabs with the rice are Shami kebabs and often eaten with pilau and biryani. The meat which is normally either mutton or chicken is cooked with spices and chana dal and then semi pounded until half smooth hence the smooth texture.

author: @shaheer.jameel
comment: Ok, so being a Pakistani, I prefer biryani over kebab pulao as well. Biryani Rice is steamed with gravy full of spices and pulao rice are steamed with chicken broth. Biryani usually are full of flavor and spices. Shami Kebab in pulao are made with mixture of lengils and chicken/beef. The reason for pulao kebab having so many reviews and famous is, First it is very affordable, secondly it is better for eating daily compared to biryani due to less spices and affordability. Savour pulao was initially launched in Rawalpindi and made famous by daily workers, labor and students. Have fun in Islamabad Hugh. H&N foods in Islamabad and Tribes are 2 good spots you can try out for desi food.

author: @satyammishra2090
comment:
Lesser Known Fact:

Thereâ€™s a small town on KPKâ€™s M1 called Lahor near Swabi. 

Known by few to once have been an ancient town on the Indus carrying immense historic importance for the Hindus, Buddhists and Muslims of South Asia. 

A town of scholars, monks, and warriors 1/n (ğŸ§µ)

Lahor, also known as Chota Lahore, is a small town lying near the confluence of the Kabul and Indus rivers in KPK. 

However in the ancient times this town was known as Salatura, home of the grammarian Panini, the Monk Marananta, and the last town of Al-Muhallabâ€™s foray.

Panini was an ancient Hindu grammarian from Salatura who lived between the 6th and 4th centuries BCE and was one of the first people in the world to work on descriptive linguistics and certainly the first to write a treatise on Sanskrit grammar.

His work consisting of over 3000 aphorisms, the Astadhyayi, marks the transition from Vedic Sanskrit to classical Sanskrit and was used for centuries after him and won him much acclaim even from modern linguists. 

There was apparently a statue of him in Salatura at some point.

Marananta was a Buddhist monk from Salatura credited to be amongst the first to introduce Buddhism to the Korean Peninsula in the late 4th century. 

Using the Silk Road, Marananta is believed to have travelled from Gandhara through China to reach the Korean Peninsula in 384 CE.

Marananta travelled to the kingdom of Baekje and preached Buddhism to the royal house and with support of the ruler built the kingdomâ€™s first Buddhist temple and trained 10 monks. About a century and a half later, Buddhism in Baekje would reach its golden era.

Though pertinent to mention is that by further research Iâ€™ve discovered the generally accepted theory of Marananta being from Salatura to have a rather weak basis. There needs to be further work conducted by Korean and Pakistani archaeologists and historians in this regard.

Salatura was also one of the few south Asian cities to be mentioned in the early Islamic historiographical work the â€œFutuh Al-Buldanâ€ and also one of the first towns in the region to witness Muslim activity due to the foray Al-Muhallab.

Al-Muhallab Ibn Sufra was an Muslim general who led the first charge of the Muslims into todayâ€™s Khyber Pukhtunkhwa in 644 CE during the rule of the Huns. 

The historian Baladhuri mentions 2 cities: Al-Bannah (Bannu Basin) and Al-Ahwar (Lahor/Salatura).

Though the attack was successful, no permanent hold over the region was made but an important possible strategic aim was achieved. Forces of Zabulistan were possibly scattered and barred from regrouping against Ibn Samuraâ€™s siege which lead to the fall of Kabul to the Muslims.

Though due to a dearth of information we donâ€™t know how large of an effect this foray till Salatura had but the existence of early Islamic tombs, mentions of Muslims traders in Hund and the later tomb of Sinan Ibn Salmah show us that the Muslim activity in the region increased.

Though Salatura would find another possible mention later on by some historians, itâ€™s importance vaned even further with time. 

It is all but a small town on the motorway now, a small town with a small secret of its extremely illustrious past.

author: @zaidsultan7310
comment:
Lahore, city of gardens and dreams,
Where history and modernity gleams,
With treasures of art and culture so rare,
And a soul that's vibrant, alive and aware.

In the ancient walls of Lahore Fort,
Mughal grandeur and glory still court,
While Badshahi Mosque stands tall and proud,
A marvel of faith, beauty, and crowd.

The bustling bazaars of Anarkali,
And the lanes of Food Street so jolly,
Are a feast for senses and appetite,
With flavors and colors that ignite.

From the stunning Shalimar Gardens' grace,
To the peaceful Wazir Khan Mosque's embrace,
Lahore's architecture is a sight to behold,
A blend of past, present, and stories untold.

The people of Lahore are warm and kind,
Their hospitality knows no bind,
With a love for food, music, and dance,
And a zest for life that's infectious, by chance.

Lahore, city of gardens and dreams,
Where every corner a history beam,
A city that's alive, with a heart so true,
Lahore, I can't help but fall in love with you.

author: @amarnathjha8319
comment:
I love Lahore, Lahoriat friends in USA and Lahore stories.
Lahore was originally LUVPURAM and this City(NAGAR) was eastablished by Shri Luv, older son of Shri Ram of Bharatbarsh (with capital at Ayodhya).
Mere priya Lhori dost, Hindu Muslim, Sikh Budh jhagre se uper utho aur apne Itihas(TARIKH) ko pahchano aur use sahi sahi apne children ko transfer karo.
JO koum apni Tarikh bhul jati hai wo Tarikhi panne se hat jati hai. Apak itihas bahut purana hai. Ancient time se LUVPURAM (Lahore) wahin khara hai. Pahle Vedic Arya ne ise basaya, fir Budh ne age barhaya, fir Islam ne ise aur naye naye buildings jorkar age barhaya. Fir Sikhon ne age barhaya. Fir Angrej ne aakar aur bistar diya. 
Pure duniya ke log Lahore aana chahte hain. Yadi Egypt aur Greece tourist map par hai  to Lahore ko bhi hona chahiye. 
Ab Lahore ko kisse khatra hai?Ise duniya ka top business center banye. English aur Urdu ke sath sath Sanskrit ko jinda kijiye.
Sanskrit ko Byakaran(grammar) dene bale koi aur nahi, balki Lahori Shri Panini  hi to the!.
Lahore ke Tarikh per research hona chahiye. Is per kitaben likhi jani chahiye.
Lahore ka appreciator - ek USA based Sanatani.

author: @Sololife07
comment:
A Hindu legend based on oral traditions holds that Lahore, known in ancient times as Nokhar (City of Lava in Sanskrit),[1] was founded by Prince Lava,[2] the son of the goddess Sita and Rama; Kasur was founded by his twin brother Prince Kusha.[3] To this day, Lahore Fort has a vacant Lava temple dedicated to Lava (also pronounced Loh, hence Loh-awar or "The Fort of Loh").[4] It is one of various etymological theory of Lahore's origin.

Rama fighting Lava and Kusha.
The oldest authentic document about Lahore was written anonymously in 982. It is called Hudud-i-Alam (The Regions of the World).[5] In 1927 it was translated into English by Vladimir Fedorovich Minorsky and published in Lahore. In this document, Lahore is referred to as a small shehr (city) with "impressive temples, large markets and huge orchards." It refers to "two major markets around which dwellings exist," and it also mentions "the mud walls that enclose these two dwellings to make it one." The original document is currently held in the British Museum.[6] Lahore was called by different names throughout history. To date there is no conclusive evidence as to when it was founded. Some historians trace the history of the city as far back as 4000 years ago.[7] However, historically, it has been proved that Lahore is at least 2,000 years old. Lying on the main trade and invasion routes to South Asia, Lahore has been ruled and plundered by a number of dynasties and hordes.

author: @rashidawan-b4t
comment: Good to see all but i m sorry u did not mention the full details of these jail.This was a sub jail that was made by dictator Ayub khan and many political workers were detained  there for years.One of a great man the grand son of Nawab Moshan ul Mulk name Hassan Nasir was killed in these prison cell and many political workers of People,s party after Bhutto,s hanging were tourched there.Even my educated family members remained here in the prison in 1981-82 .it was a terrible place and i use to go there at that time to see my uncles who was facing Zia ul haq cruelty and facing political imprisonment.This tourcher cell was finished by Junejo government in 1986.

author: @Gulchih
comment: Keep a towel with you during the daytime for your mum, love. Heatstrokes are common at this time of year and she needs something to protect her from direct sunlight. She should wear a light shrug too but a white towel to cover the torso is necessary if going outside during the peak sun hours. I fainted once in the outdoor market as I didn't take it seriously. Also after returning to your room don't shower straight away, the sudden temperature change in the body can cause blood vessels to expand and cause hemorrhage, God forbid. Wait 15 mins and then shower if you need to. And remember to drink lots of liquid especially lemonade, which has some sugar & salts because in sweating a lot of the body's salts are lost. If you take these precautions nothing to worry about!

12:00 itâ€™s a hot country thing. Iâ€™m from Hyderabad in India and because itâ€™s so hot during the day, nobody really likes going out in the day (unless they have to for work or school). When people invite you home for dinner, they expect you to arrive around 8-9, dinner is served at 10, and everyone starts saying goodbye at 12am and finally leaves at 1am.
The Middle East is also a lot like this - nobody wants to be out walking in the heat at mid-day so street life only really starts around 1-2 hours before sunset.

author: @Rocky45415
comment: Apologies for the long comment but I thought I should share my thoughts..I am from india MP. I had the privilege of visiting Pakistan in December of last year, and I must express that it was an exceptionally rewarding experience. Despite having traveled to numerous countries, I found Pakistan to be particularly enchanting, largely due to the warmth and hospitality of its people. The genuine kindness and open-heartedness exhibited by the Pakistani people left an amazing impression on me, and I hold fond memories of the gracious welcome extended to me during my time there. Pakistan holds a special place in my heart, and I am grateful for the opportunity to have experienced its rich culture and hospitality firsthand.Wanna say something more....The natural beauty of pakistan is something else..I think if pak govt looks forward i think pakistan can become number 1 for tourists...I visited kashmir,KPK and skardu in pakistan...The natural beauty of all these places gave me peaceful vibe.. Pakistan is the only country where i wanna go again and again..The hospitality of poor people in pakistan even if they don't have personal houses,was unbelievable..Even after telling them that i am a Hindu still they treated me like a king.... Really enthusiastic journey of my life...

author: @IWouldEat
comment:
Eating food outside too much, know the side effects.
*********************************************************
Often people are fond of eating outside, people enjoy outdoor eating with their friends and family. At the same time, some people have the compulsion to eat outside. Students and professionals living alone away from their homes are forced to eat outside food. Everyday eating out is not good for your health. It can harm you in many ways. If you are planning to eat out with your friends today, it is better that you cancel your plans. It is not good for your own health.

Actually, you may not be aware of this fact, but eating out regularly can actually spoil your health. It increases the production of a chemical called phthalates in the body and damages your health in the worst way. It also upsets the natural hormonal balance and affects your overall health. In addition, there are many more factors that suggest that one should not eat out often or regularly. Let us know why eating outside is often not a healthy option.

author: @aaishaa19
comment: People in Pakistan are incredibly kind and hospitable, often refusing to take money from their guestsâ€”100 out of 100 for their generosity! However, itâ€™s truly shameful when some foreign visitors exploit this kindness. They enjoy meals worth 1,500 PKR but offer only 300 PKR, or drink lassi worth 150 PKR x 2 while holding a mere 70 PKR to pay.
